__NOTOC__
[[Image:View across Cleeve Common - geograph.org.uk - 38060.jpg|Cleeve Common is designated a biological and geological site|thumb|250px]]

This is a '''list of the [[Sites of Special Scientific Interest]] (SSSIs) in [[Gloucestershire]]'''. [[Natural England]], the designating body for SSSIs in [[England]], uses the [[Metropolitan and non-metropolitan counties of England|1974-1996 county system]], and this list follows the same approach. Some sites you may expect to find here could therefore be in the [[List of SSSIs in Avon|Avon]] list.<ref>For example, [[Midger]] and [[Lower Woods]] are included in the [[List of SSSIs in Avon|Avon list]]</ref> It may also be that a site may on the borders of more than one county.<ref>For example, see [http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/Special/sssi/sssi_details.cfm?sssi_id=1001017 Natural England citation] for 'The Malvern Hills' (retrieved 2012-08-21)</ref> It may also be on the country borders.<ref>For example, see [http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/Special/sssi/sssi_details.cfm?sssi_id=1003580 Natural England citation] for 'Upper Wye Gorge' (retrieved 2012-08-21)</ref>

[[Natural England]] chooses a site because of its [[fauna]], [[plant|flora]], [[geology|geological]] or physiographical features.<ref>{{cite web|title=Notification of SSSIs |work=Natural England |url=http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/special/sssi/notification.cfm |accessdate=2012-08-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120515062100/http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/special/sssi/notification.cfm |archivedate=2012-05-15 |df= }}</ref> As of 2012, there are 121 sites designated in this [[Area of Search]], of which 69 have been designated due to their biological interest, 32 due to their geological interest, and 20 for both.<ref>{{cite web | title=SSSIs in Gloucestershire | work=Natural England | url=http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/special/sssi/searchresults.cfm?sssi_name=&frmcounty=1016| accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref>

Gloucestershire has 3 [[Areas of Outstanding Natural Beauty]] being the [[Cotswolds]], [[Malvern Hills]], and the [[Wye Valley]] (the latter is also partly in Wales).  These areas may include several SSSIs, or be named an SSSI as is the case for the Malvern Hills.<ref>{{cite web | title=Natural England information and map of AONBs | work=Natural England | url=http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designations/aonb/default.aspx | accessdate=2012-10-03}}</ref>

Gloucestershire has 2 designated [[Ramsar site]]s being the [[Severn Estuary]] and [[Walmore Common]] both SSSIs.<ref>{{cite web | title=Joint Nature Conservation Committee Listing of Ramsars | work=DEFRA | url=http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/page-1389 | accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref> These two sites are also designated as [[Special Protection Area]]s (SPA) under the EC Directive on the conservation of Wild Birds.<ref>{{cite web | title=Joint Nature Conservation Committee Listing of Special Protection Areas | work=DEFRA | url=http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/page-1400 | accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref>

Gloucestershire has 7 recognised [[Special Area of Conservation|Special Areas of Conservation]] (SAC), several of which bring together more than one SSSI.  These are: [[Cotswold Commons And Beechwoods|Cotswold Beechwoods]]; [[Dixton Wood]]; [[River Wye|River Wye/ Afon Gwy]]; [[Rodborough Common]]; [[Severn Estuary]]; Wye Valley and Forest of Dean Bat Sites/ Safleoedd Ystlumod Dyffryn Gwy a Fforest y Ddena; Wye Valley Woodlands/ Coetiroedd Dyffryn Gwy.<ref>{{cite web | title=Joint Nature Conservation Committee Listing of Special Areas of Conservation | work=DEFRA | url=http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/ProtectedSites/SACselection/SAC_list.asp | accessdate=2012-09-23}}</ref>

[[Highbury Wood]] SSSI<ref>{{cite web | title= Natural England NNR citation and map for Highbury Wood NNR| work=Natural England | url= http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designatedareas/nnr/1006076.aspx| accessdate=2012-09-24}}</ref> and the [[Cotswold Commons and Beechwoods]] SSSI<ref>{{cite web | title=Natural England NNR citation and map for the Cotswolds Commons and Beechwoods | work=Natural England | url=http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designations/nnr/1006044.aspx | accessdate=2012-09-27}}</ref> are [[national nature reserve (United Kingdom)|national nature reserve]]s (NNR). [[Lady Park Wood]] (part of the wood is in Gloucestershire and part in Monmouthshire) is a national nature reserve.<ref>{{cite web | title=Natural England NNR citation and map for Lady Park Wood (Gloucestershire) | work=Natural England | url=http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designatedareas/nnr/1006088.aspx | accessdate=2012-09-27}}</ref>

A significant number of the SSSIs are recognised by the relevant local authorities as '''Key Wildlife Sites''' and '''[[Regionally Important Geological Sites|Regionally Important Geological/Geomorphological Sites]]'''. There are c. 800 recognised Key Wildlife Sites in Gloucestershire.<ref>{{cite web | title=Key Wildlife Sites information | work=Gloucestershire Wildlife Trust| url=http://www.gloucestershirewildlifetrust.co.uk/what-we-do/local-nature-conservation/conservation-areas/key-wildlife-sites | accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref>

For other counties, see [[List of SSSIs by Area of Search]].

