==Subdisciplines of ecology, and subdiscipline classification==
Ecology is a broad discipline comprising many sub-disciplines. The field of ecology can be sub-divided according to several classification schemes:

===By level of complexity or scope===
Arranged from lowest to highest complexity:
* {{annotated link|Ecophysiology}}, or {{annotated link|Behavioral ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Population ecology|aka=autoecology}}
* {{annotated link|Community (ecology)|Community ecology|aka=synecology}}
* {{annotated link|Ecosystem ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Systems ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Landscape ecology}}

===By organisms under study===
* {{annotated link|Animal ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Behavioral ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Biogeography}}
* {{annotated link|Insect ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Microbial ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Paleoecology}}
* {{annotated link|Plant ecology}}

===By biome under study===
* {{annotated link|Benthic ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Desert ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Forest ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Grassland ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Marine ecology}} 
* {{annotated link|Aquatic ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Urban ecology}}

===By geographic or climatic area under study===
* {{annotated link|Arctic ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Polar ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Tropical ecology}}

===By spatial scale under study===
* {{annotated link|Global ecology}} 
* {{annotated link|Landscape ecology}} 
* {{annotated link|Landscape limnology}}
* {{annotated link|Spatial ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Macroecology}}
* {{annotated link|Microecology}}
* {{annotated link|Microbial ecology}} 
* {{annotated link|Molecular ecology}}

===By ecological aspects or phenomena under investigation===
* {{annotated link|Chemical ecology}} &ndash; which deals with the ecological role of biological chemicals used in a wide range of areas including defense against predators and attraction of mates;
* {{annotated link|Ecophysiology}} &ndash; which studies the interaction of physiological traits with the abiotic environment;
* {{annotated link|Ecotoxicology}} &ndash; which looks at the ecological role of toxic chemicals (often [[pollutant]]s, but also naturally occurring compounds);
* {{annotated link|Evolutionary ecology}} &ndash; or [[ecoevolution]] which looks at evolutionary changes in the context of the populations and communities in which the organisms exist;
* {{annotated link|Fire ecology}} &ndash; which looks at the role of fire in the environment of plants and animals and its effect on ecological communities;
* {{annotated link|Functional ecology}} &ndash; the study of the roles, or functions, that certain species (or groups thereof) play in an ecosystem;
* {{annotated link|Genetic ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Soil ecology}} &ndash; the ecology of the pedosphere;

===By technique used for investigation===
* {{annotated link|Field ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Quantitative ecology}}
* {{annotated link|Theoretical ecology}} &ndash; the development of ecological theory, usually with mathematical, statistical and/or computer modeling tools;

===By environmental approach===
* {{annotated link|Applied ecology}} &ndash; the practice of employing ecological principles and understanding to solve real world problems (includes [[agroecology]] and [[conservation biology]]);
* {{annotated link|conservation biology|Conservation ecology}} &ndash; which studies how to reduce the risk of species extinction;
* {{annotated link|Deep ecology}} &ndash; an ecological and environmental philosophy promoting the inherent worth of living beings regardless of their instrumental utility to human needs, plus a radical restructuring of modern human societies in accordance with such ideas.
* {{annotated link|Ecosophy}} &ndash; philosophy of ecological harmony or equilibrium.
* {{annotated link|Restoration ecology}} &ndash; which attempts to understand the ecological basis needed to restore impaired or damaged ecosystems.
* {{annotated link|Speciesism}} &ndash; involves the assignment of different values, rights, or special consideration to individuals solely on the basis of their species membership.
* {{annotated link|Technocentrism}} &ndash; value system that is centered on technology and its ability to control and protect the environment.

===Ecology-involved interdisciplinary fields===
* {{annotated link|Agroecology}}
* {{annotated link|Biogeochemistry}}
* {{annotated link|Ecological design}}
* {{annotated link|Ecological economics}}
