{{Infobox observatory |name = Zimmerwald Observatory |background = |image = Sternwarte ZImmerwald.jpg |image_size = 200px |alt = View of the dome-shaped Zimmerwald Obeservatory |caption = The Zimmerwald Observatory in 2009 |organization = [[University of Berne]] |code=026 |location = near [[Zimmerwald]], [[Canton of Berne]], [[Switzerland]] |coords = {{coord|46.87667|7.46500|type:landmark_region:CH-BE_source:USNO/HMNAO|display=inline,title}} |altitude = |weather = |established = 1956 |closed = |website = {{URL|https://web.archive.org/web/20071224003808/http://www.aiub.unibe.ch/content/zimmerwald/index_eng.html|www.aiub.unibe.ch}} |telescope1_name = ZIMLAT |telescope1_type = 1-meter Laser and Astrometric Telescope |telescope2_name = |telescope2_type = |telescope3_name = |telescope3_type = |telescope4_name = |telescope4_type = }}
The '''Zimmerwald Observatory''' ({{lang-de|'''Observatorium Zimmerwald'''}}) is an [[astronomy|astronomical]] [[observatory]] owned and operated by the AIUB, the Astronomical Institute of the [[University of Bern]]. Built in 1956, it is located at [[Zimmerwald]], 10 kilometers south of [[Bern]], Switzerland.
Numerous [[comet]]s and [[asteroid]]s have been discovered by [[Paul Wild (Swiss astronomer)|Paul Wild]] (1925–2014) at Zimmerwald Observatory, most notably comet [[81P/Wild]], which was visited by NASA's [[Stardust (spacecraft)|Stardust space probe]] in 2004. The [[main belt]] asteroid [[1775 Zimmerwald]] has been named after the location of the observatory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi#top |title=1775 Zimmerwald (1969 JA) |work=[[JPL]] – Small-Body Database Browser |accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref>
The 1-meter aperture ZIMLAT telescope was inaugurated in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |title=The ZIMLAT Telescope |url=http://cmslive3.unibe.ch/unibe/philnat/aiub/content/zimmerwald/the_zimlat_telescope/index_eng.html |work=Universität Bern, Astronomisches Institut, Zimmerwald Observatory |date=3 August 2007}}</ref>
